n all sources, so they are flagged as list_columns. Kept transformations minimal, avoiding name/artist/title casing because target preserves mixed original casing. Included label only for discogs due to prior low label accuracy and visible whitespace-cleanup safety.",\n  "datasets": {\n    "discogs": {\n      "input_path": "output/runs/20260322_171209_music/normalization/attempt_2/discogs.csv",\n      "output_path": "output/runs/20260322_171209_music/normalization/attempt_3/discogs.csv",\n      "row_count": 22627,\n      "id_column": "id",\n      "spec_applied": {\n        "release-date": {\n          "output_type": "datetime",\n          "date_format": "%Y-%m-%dT%H:%M:%S.%f",\n          "on_failure": "keep"\n        },\n        "release-country": {\n          "strip_whitespace": true,\n          "country_format": "name",\n          "on_failure": "keep"\n        },\n        "duration": {\n          "output_type": "string",\n          "on_failure": "keep"\n        },\n        "label": {\n          "strip_whitespace": true,\n          "on_failure": "keep"\n        },\n        "tracks_track_duration": {\n          "strip_whitespace": true,\n          "on_failure": "keep"\n        }\n      },\n      "list_columns_applied": [\n        "tracks_track_name",\n        "tracks_track_position",\n        "tracks_track_duration"\n      ]\n    },\n    "lastfm": {\n      "input_path": "output/runs/20260322_171209_music/normalization/attempt_2/lastfm.csv",\n      "output_path": "output/runs/20260322_171209_music/normalization/attempt_3/lastfm.csv",\n      "row_count": 9865,\n      "id_column": "id",\n      "spec_applied": {\n        "duration": {\n          "output_type": "string",\n          "on_failure": "keep"\n        },\n        "tracks_track_duration": {\n          "strip_whitespace": true,\n          "on_failure": "keep"\n        }\n      },\n      "list_columns_applied": [\n        "tracks_track_name",\n        "tracks_track_position",\n        "tracks_track_duration"\n      ]\n    },\n    "musicbrainz": {\n      "input_path": "output/runs/20260322_171209_music/normalization/attempt_2/musicbrainz.csv",\n      "output_path": "output/runs/20260322_171209_music/normalization/attempt_3/musicbrainz.csv",\n      "row_count": 4763,\n      "id_column": "id",\n      "spec_applied": {\n        "release-date": {\n          "output_type": "datetime",\n          "date_format": "%Y-%m-%dT%H:%M:%S.%f",\n          "on_failure": "keep"\n        },\n        "release-country": {\n          "strip_whitespace": true,\n          "country_format": "name",\n          "on_failure": "keep"\n        },\n        "duration": {\n          "output_type": "string",\n          "on_failure": "keep"\n        },\n        "tracks_track_duration": {\n          "strip_whitespace": true,\n          "on_failure": "keep"\n        }\n      },\n      "list_columns_applied": [\n        "tracks_track_name",\n        "tracks_track_position",\n        "tracks_track_duration"\n      ]\n    }\n  },\n  "warnings": [],\n  "acceptance_gate": {\n    "requested": false,\n    "request": {},\n    "pending": {}\n  },\n  "reverted_to_original": false,\n  "created_at": "2026-03-22T17:32:42.803062"\n}\n    \n        Create evaluation code that:\n        - Uses the correct fusion strategy\n        - Loads the fused output\n        - Loads the gold standard evaluation set (validation in sealed mode, otherwise test)\n        - Prints structured evaluation metrics\n        - Prints chosen evaluation functions in a compact one-line summary\n        - If helper modules are imported from local files (e.g., list_normalization), use a robust fallback import pattern that works from output/code execution context.\n        - Does NOT require exact matching everywhere by default.\n\n        EVALUATION ROBUSTNESS RULES (MANDATORY):\n- Use validation-set representation as the normalization target for evaluation.\n- Normalize fused and gold columns to the SAME representation before evaluating.\n- For country-like columns, infer and apply a shared normalize_country output_format from the evaluation set (alpha_2/alpha_3/numeric/name/official_name).\n- For free-text/list-like columns, avoid strict exact comparisons unless values are canonical identifiers.\n  Prefer tokenized_match with an explicit threshold (for example 0.7-0.9) instead of exact-only semantics.\n- If using set-based comparison on textual lists, first canonicalize list elements consistently across fused and gold.\n- Choose the right evaluation function per attribute type:\n  * tokenized_match: names, titles, labels, artists, text fields (handles word reordering like "The Beatles" vs "Beatles, The")\n  * year_only_match: dates where only the year matters\n  * set_equality_match: list-like columns (tracks, genres, categories)\n  * numeric_tolerance_match: durations, prices, ratings (use reasonable tolerance)\n  * numeric_tolerance_match: also use for year/count columns stored as floats (e.g. publish_year, page_count) —\n    cast both fused and gold values to int before comparison to avoid 274.0 != 274 mismatches\n  * exact_match: IDs, codes, boolean fields\n- If the gold set does NOT contain a column (i.e. it is absent or all-null), do NOT evaluate that column.\n  Only evaluate columns that are present and meaningful in BOTH the fused and gold datasets.\n- IMPORTANT: When the gold set has a parent column (e.g. "tracks") but the fused output has sub-columns\n  derived from it (e.g. "tracks_track_name", "tracks_track_duration", "tracks_track_position"),\n  DROP the sub-columns from evaluation unless they have explicit corresponding columns in the gold set.\n  Evaluating derived sub-columns against a non-existent gold column produces zero accuracy and wastes\n  investigation cycles. Only evaluate attributes that have a direct 1:1 column match in the gold set.\n- IMPORTANT: Before evaluation, coerce numeric-like columns (publish_year, page_count, year, count, rating, score)\n  to a consistent type in BOTH fused and gold DataFrames. Common pattern:\n    for col in numeric_cols:\n        df[col] = pd.to_numeric(df[col], errors=\'coerce\')\n        if df[col].dropna().apply(lambda x: float(x).is_integer()).all():\n            df[col] = df[col].astype(\'Int64\')  # nullable int avoids 274.0 vs 274 mismatches\n  This prevents false mismatches from float vs int representation differences.\n- If the fused output contains an "eval_id" column, use fused_id_column="eval_id" (NOT "_id" or "id").\n  The eval_id column is pre-computed to map cluster IDs back to validation-set source IDs.\n        \n            Evaluation reasoning from prior pipeline run:\n            {\n  "action": "decide",\n  "diagnosis": "The main remaining fixable errors are pre-fusion normalization/representation issues, not blocking or matching. Blocking/matching are healthy (all correspondence files non-empty, F1\\u22480.87\\u20130.90, no blocking-recall issues). The clearest improvable attributes are label and release-date, but their error pattern is still dominated by missing fused values caused by source-format/null handling rather than wrong entity pairs. The list-valued track attributes remain largely structurally limited because fused outputs often contain different tracklists than validation, not just different formatting. Current fusion already uses the resolver family previously indicated, and 18 attributes are >85%, so those should be preserved. The next fix should therefore target normalization so source values align exactly with the validation representation before fusion, especially release-date datetime completion/formatting and preservation of label values from discogs, while avoiding regressions on protected attributes.",\n  "next_node": "normalization_node",\n  "reasoning": "Protected attributes already performing well and should not be changed in fusion: duration, release-country, tracks_track_position, artist, name, plus the other high-performing attributes above 85%. Matching is not the bottleneck. For label, source-vs-validation evidence is decisive: discogs is 100% exact and non-null, so the remaining misses indicate the discogs label is not consistently surviving in a usable normalized form into fusion/evaluation. For release-date, all sources have 0% exact but high fuzzy agreement, which means validation expects a canonical timestamp representation with default month/day completion; this is a normalization problem first. The worst list attributes show structural disagreement in content/length, so fusion changes there would not recover much and risk harming stable attributes. Because pipeline_adaption cannot add preprocessing and the needed fixes are source transformations before fusion, normalization_node is the correct route.",\n  "ceiling_assessment": "A realistic ceiling remains around the reported 84.5% with the current structure. Most remaining headroom is in label and release-date. Track-name and track-duration are structurally limited by source disagreement, so even perfect normalization will not fully close the gap. A careful normalization pass should recover several points overall without disturbing protected attributes.",\n  "recommendations": [\n    {\n      "attribute": "label",\n      "issue": "Validation comparison shows discogs matches perfectly (100% exact, 100% non-null), yet fused output is often blank. This indicates label values need to be preserved/standardized pre-fusion rather than changing the resolver.",\n      "fix": "In normalization_node, apply conservative string normalization to discogs.label only: strip surrounding whitespace, normalize Unicode punctuation/spacing, convert empty strings/placeholders to null, but preserve original casing/content. Ensure no transformation drops non-empty labels. Keep fusion as prefer_higher_trust with discogs highest.",\n      "resolver_reasoning": "prefer_higher_trust(discogs > lastfm > musicbrainz) is already the best resolver because source-vs-validation evidence shows discogs is perfect while the others are effectively unusable for label. Alternatives perform worse: voting can fail when only discogs has a value, longest/shortest_string are irrelevant for label semantics, and favour_sources duplicates the same preference less explicitly than trust-based selection. The issue is not resolver choice but making sure normalized discogs values remain available and non-empty at fusion time.",\n      "class": "improvable",\n      "expected_impact": 0.049\n    },\n    {\n      "attribute": "release-date",\n      "issue": "All sources are fuzzy-close but 0% exact, showing the validation expects canonical timestamps with imputed month/day/time components. Current misses are mostly blank fused values plus format granularity mismatch.",\n      "fix": "In normalization_node, standardize release-date in discogs and musicbrainz to the exact validation format YYYY-MM-DDT00:00:00.000, with explicit completion rules: YYYY -> YYYY-01-01T00:00:00.000 and YYYY-MM -> YYYY-MM-01T00:00:00.000 where source granularity is partial. Preserve nulls only when truly missing. Keep current fusion resolver for release-date.",\n      "resolver_reasoning": "The comparison evidence supports keeping a consensus-style resolver for release-date because no single source is exact, while discogs/lastfm/musicbrainz are all similarly fuzzy-close. prefer_higher_trust would overcommit to one imperfect source; earliest could systematically bias dates; longest/shortest are inapplicable. The primary problem is representational mismatch to validation, so normalization before fusion is the highest-value fix.",\n      "class": "improvable",\n      "expected_impact": 0.026\n    },\n    {\n      "attribute": "tracks_track_name",\n      "issue": "Errors are dominated by list mismatches with differing content/length; examples show many releases have fundamentally different tracklists across sources, not merely casing or delimiter issues.",\n      "fix": "Only apply safe list normalization in normalization_node: parse list-like strings consistently, trim elements, normalize quotes/dashes/whitespace, remove empty items, and serialize stably. Do not change fusion yet.",\n      "resolver_reasoning": "No resolver is likely to materially outperform current source-preference logic because the ceiling is already equal to observed accuracy, indicating structural limitation. union/intersection/voting would change semantics and may regress rows already correct. Minimal normalization may remove superficial noise, but this attribute should not drive fusion changes.",\n      "class": "structurally_limited",\n      "expected_impact": 0.0\n    },\n    {\n      "attribute": "tracks_track_duration",\n      "issue": "Track-duration lists disagree in both values and list lengths; several mismatches reflect extra/missing tracks rather than formatting alone.",\n      "fix": "In normalization_node, coerce list elements to canonical integer-string tokens, remove blanks, and ensure stable serialization only. Avoid fusion-rule changes.",\n      "resolver_reasoning": "This attribute is at its current structural ceiling. maximum/minimum/median are inappropriate because the field is a list aligned to track ordering, not a scalar numeric measurement. union/intersection would distort positional semantics. Safe normalization can reduce representation noise, but major gains are not achievable under the current source data.",\n      "class": "structurally_limited",\n      "expected_impact": 0.0\n    }\n  ]\n}\n            \n            Compact summary from the prior reasoning:\n            {\n  "root_cause": "The main remaining fixable errors are pre-fusion normalization/representation issues, not blocking or matching. Blocking/matching are healthy (all correspondence files non-empty, F1\\u22480.87\\u20130.90, no blocking-recall issues). The clearest improvable attributes are label and release-date, but their error pattern is still dominated by missing fused values caused by source-format/null han